instruction:
I'm writing a NeurIPS paper about a new model architecture for processing and generating long texts. Here are some facts about the paper:
* The main trick is to replace some of the attention heads with an exponential moving average, where the decay rate is learned for each head. We call this architecture ExeMA.
* On language modeling, the perplexity difference between our model and a vanilla transformer is negligible, but that's because next-token prediction is almost always a local task, so perplexity won't be sensitive enough to detect any improvements in long-range understanding.
* However, on the SCROLLS benchmark, our model improves by 10% over the baseline.
* We also have a new metric for measuring coherence in generated text (CoGnaTe), where our model generates text that is 43% more coherent than the baseline.
Help me write the paper's introduction.
output_1:
Here is the introduction of the paper:

Attention mechanisms are crucial for modern neural language models.
However, despite their success, these models lack an explicit memory, as the state of each layer depends only on the previous layer and the input.
To address this limitation, we propose ExeMA, an exponential moving average of the model's previous state, to improve the model's long-range understanding and generate more coherent text.
We conduct experiments on language modeling and text generation benchmarks.
The results show that ExeMA improves the model's long-range understanding without negatively affecting its short-range comprehension.
Moreover, our model generates text that is significantly more coherent than the baseline.

The rest of the paper is structured as follows:
Section 2 introduces the background and related work.
Section 3 presents the ExeMA model and the CoGnaTe metric.
Section 4 describes the experimental setup and results.
Section 5 discusses the limitations of our work and potential future directions.
Section 6 concludes the paper.
output_2:
The Transformer architecture has revolutionized the Natural Language Processing field with its unprecedented success in a wide range of language tasks. Despite its effectiveness, the local nature of attention operations prevents Transformer-based models from capturing long-range dependencies, which limits their capability in understanding long texts.
In this work, we introduce a novel Transformer architecture, ExeMA, which addresses the aforementioned issue. The core idea of ExeMA is to replace some of the attention heads with an exponential moving average of the values attended to. Our experiments show that the proposed architecture outperforms vanilla Transformers in long-range understanding and generation tasks.

instruction: I have an exercise in game of theory class that I should find all equilibriums in rock paper scissors game. Could you help me with this exercise?
output_1:
Consider the game Rock-Paper-Scissors. In this game, the players simultaneously choose one of three actions: rock, paper, or scissors. The action that beats the other two is said to "beat" them, and it wins the round against them. For instance, rock beats scissors and paper, but loses to lizard, which beats rock. This game has no equilibrium. There are two strategies (choosing rock and choosing scissors) that have the same payoff: winning against each other, but losing to paper.

This shows that there can be no equilibrium: if there were an equilibrium, there would be some action that would beat all other actions, but no action beats all other actions.
output_2: Sure, I can give you a hint.  The most common solution is “tit-for-tat”, where each player always chooses the same option as the last player.  There is another solution where each player always chooses a different option, and the players alternate.  This is called “Cyclic” strategy.  And there is a third solution, called “Tit for Tat with Forgetting”, where a player will choose the same option as the last player, but if the player ever sees the same option twice in a row, then the player will switch to a random option.  So in your solution, you can find all three of these.

instruction: Who are some eminent scholars of the Quechua language?

The Quechua language is a language family that includes many dialects spoken in South America. The most important Quechuan languages are North, South, and Central Quechua. There are approximately 8–10 million native speakers of Quechuan languages. The Quechua language is spoken by a variety of indigenous peoples of South America, particularly in Peru and Bolivia.

Quechua scholars include:

*  Julio C. Tello: Peruvian linguist and Quechua scholar. He is an expert in Quechua phonology, morphology and sociolinguistics. He has published a Quechua dictionary and many academic papers on Quechua.
*  Henry J. Miller: Professor at the University of Texas at Austin, he is an expert in Quechua and Aymara grammar. He is one of the few Western scholars who is fluent in Quechua.
*  Guillermo Lohmann: Professor at the University of Chile. He has published a Quechua grammar book and several other works on Quechua.
*  Alejandro Echeverría: Peruvian linguist and Quechua scholar. He is an expert in Quechua phonology and morphology. He has published several books on Quechua.
*  Víctor M. Valle: Bolivian linguist and Quechua scholar. He is an expert in Quechua phonology and morphology. He has published several books on Quechua.
*  Rosalina Guillén: Peruvian linguist and Quechua scholar. She is an expert in Quechua phonology and morphology. She has published several books on Quechua.
*  Ronald W. Little: Professor at the University of Texas at Austin. He has published several books on Quechua.
*  John V. Murra: American anthropologist and Quechua scholar. He was one of the first Western scholars to study Quechua. He published a Quechua grammar book and several other works on Quechua.
*  Luis E. Luna: Peruvian linguist and Quechua scholar. He is an expert in Quechua phonology and morphology. He has published several books on Quechua.
*  Roland H. G. Yáñez: Bolivian linguist and Quechua scholar. He is an expert in Quechua phonology and morphology. He has published several books on Quechua.

These are just some of the many scholars who have contributed to the study of Quechua. There are many more who have made important contributions to our understanding of this fascinating language.

instruction: How do I find out which process is using my webcam on macOS?
output_1:
Run the following command in a Terminal window:

```
kextstat | grep Vid
```

This will list all the kexts (kernel extensions) loaded on your Mac, and check which ones use the `Vid` IOKit call. `Vid` is an IOKit call that is used to access the video input devices, including the webcam.
output_2: To find out which process is using your webcam, you can use the “Activity Monitor” application.  This application can be found in the Utilities folder in the Applications folder.  Once you have the “Activity Monitor” application open, you can use the drop-down menu at the top to select the “Camera” process.  This will show you all of the applications that are currently using your webcam.  You can then quit the applications that you don’t want using your webcam.

instruction: What's a good itenary for a trip to Vegas? Planning a trip for 3.5 days, please exclude any museums
output_1:
Here is an itinerary for a 3.5 day trip to Vegas.

Day 1:
* Morning: Have breakfast at The Buffet at TI (best value for the money and no lines for the weekday breakfast)
* Afternoon: Check out the Venetian for some indoor/air conditioned sightseeing, the Grand Canal Shoppes are great
* Night: Dinner at Top of the World (great food and amazing views) followed by a show at the V Theater (Blue Man Group is great)

Day 2:
* Morning: Have breakfast at Hash House a Go Go (best pancakes ever and the portions are massive)
* Afternoon: Check out The Mob Museum and then wander the Fremont Street Experience
* Night: Dinner at Joes Crab Shack (great seafood, great views and the waiters sing to you) followed by a show at one of the casinos (Caesars Palace has some great shows)

Day 3:
* Morning: Have breakfast at Peppermill (great breakfast buffet)
* Afternoon: Check out the Bellagio Conservatory and Botanical Gardens and The Mirage Volcano
* Night: Dinner at The Buffet at Aria (one of the best buffets in Vegas and no lines on weekdays) followed by a show at Caesars Palace (Love or Absinthe are great)

Day 4:
* Check out and spend the day on the Strip (go see the Bellagio Fountains, the High Roller, the Stratosphere, and the new Park MGM)
output_2:
Day 1: Arrival. Check-in to your hotel and get settled. Get dinner at Carbone, if you can get a reservation. Otherwise, find a good Italian restaurant nearby.

Day 2: Red Rock Canyon National Conservation Area. Check-in time for your evening Cirque du Soleil show (choose between Michael Jackson ONE, O, or Absinthe).

Day 3: The Neon Museum. High Roller Observation Wheel (after your morning espresso at Barista Bar). The Strip. Choose a nice steakhouse for dinner (we like B&B Ranch Steakhouse).

Day 4: Day trip to the Grand Canyon. If you can get a reservation, have dinner at Twist by Pierre Gagnaire. Otherwise, choose a nice French restaurant in the city.

Day 5: Departure.

instruction: Write an opinion piece about why diversity and inclusion is super important for the tech industry. The essay should be targeted at "tech bros", and should avoid alienating them, but instead appeal to their logic; it should explain how diversity and inclusion of women, immigrants, etc. could benefit them specifically.
output_1:
Dear Tech Bros,

You are probably reading this because someone in human resources sent this to you.  You've signed up for a diversity and inclusion training seminar.  You are wondering what the hell is going on.  You may even be a little angry.

Let me explain.

You've been working in the tech industry for a while now.  You're successful.  You've been paid a lot of money.  But over the last few years, you've noticed some changes.

There are more women at work.  There are more people of color.  There are more people who aren't from America.  There are more people who don't look like you.

There are even more people who don't think like you.

And, you're not sure what to make of it.

You're not racist, sexist, or xenophobic.  You're a good person.  But you're starting to wonder if this diversity and inclusion thing is actually going to help the company.

Here's the thing, Tech Bros.  Diversity and inclusion is good for business.

And it's good for you, too.

Let me explain.

When a company is diverse, it has access to a wider pool of talent.  That means the company can hire the best and brightest people, regardless of their background.

But diversity isn't just about hiring.  It's about keeping those people.  When a company is diverse, it has a better understanding of its customers.  It can tap into different markets and reach new audiences.

And when a company is diverse, it can innovate faster.  It can come up with new ideas and solutions that might not have occurred to a more homogeneous group.

In short, diversity makes companies more successful.  And successful companies can pay their employees more money.

So, if you're worried about diversity and inclusion, don't be.  It's good for business.  And it's good for you.

Thank you for reading this letter.  I hope I have helped to clarify some of your concerns.  If you have any questions, feel free to contact me.  I am always happy to help.

Sincerely,

[Your Name]
output_2:
Tech bros,

I hope this finds you well. 

I am writing to share some thoughts with you about diversity and inclusion in the tech industry. You may not be aware of this, but research shows that diverse teams are more creative, productive, and innovative than homogenous teams. 

Here are some of the benefits that diversity brings to the table:

1. More diverse teams can cover a wider range of perspectives and experiences, which leads to better decision-making. 

2. Diverse teams can bring a variety of skills and talents to the table, which leads to more creative solutions and better problem solving. 

3. Diversity increases the likelihood that a team will have members with different networks and connections, which can lead to new opportunities and partnerships. 

4. Diverse teams can help a company better understand and serve a more diverse customer base, which can lead to increased sales and market share. 

5. Diverse teams are more likely to incorporate multiple perspectives and viewpoints, which can lead to more innovative ideas and solutions. 

6. Diverse teams have been shown to make better decisions, be more productive, and be more innovative than homogenous teams.

As you can see, diversity is a win-win for everyone. So what can we do to encourage more diversity in the tech industry? Here are some ideas:

1. Increase outreach to women, underrepresented minorities, and other underrepresented groups.

2. Create more inclusive company cultures that value diversity and inclusion.

3. Make sure hiring managers and recruiters are trained to look for diversity in candidates.

4. Eliminate bias in hiring, promotions, and other business decisions.

5. Create mentorship programs to help women, underrepresented minorities, and other underrepresented groups advance in their careers.

6. Encourage employee resource groups that focus on diversity and inclusion.

7. Host hackathons and other events that are open to a diverse range of people.

8. Provide funding for diversity and inclusion initiatives.

9. Implement employee resource groups that focus on diversity and inclusion.

10. Be a role model for diversity and inclusion. Lead by example and encourage others to do the same.

I hope you will consider these ideas and help make the tech industry more diverse and inclusive. We all win when we embrace diversity and inclusion. 

Thanks, and I look forward to your thoughts.

instruction: What is the most efficient way to get the number of rows in a table with psycog2?
output_1:
psycopg2 is a Python database adapter for PostgreSQL. So, it is not PostgreSQL that you should ask about, but psycopg2.
In psycopg2, the `cursor.rowcount` attribute is the number of rows changed by the most recently executed statement.

```
# execute an INSERT statement
cursor.execute('INSERT INTO my_table (col1, col2) VALUES (1, 2)')

# get the number of rows inserted
rows_inserted = cursor.rowcount
```

The `cursor.rowcount` attribute is only updated when an INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE or similar statement is executed that actually changes the number of rows in the database.

If you want to get the number of rows in the entire table, you can use the `cursor.execute()` function with an `SQL SELECT COUNT(*)` query. The number of rows is returned as the `rowcount` attribute of the `cursor` object.

```
# get the number of rows in the my_table
cursor.execute('SELECT COUNT(*) FROM my_table')

# get the number of rows
rows = cursor.rowcount
```

The number of rows returned by `cursor.rowcount` may not be the exact number of rows in the table, because the `cursor.rowcount` attribute is only updated when an INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE or similar statement is executed that actually changes the number of rows in the database.

Note that the number of rows in the table can change during the execution of a single query, if that query uses a trigger.

To find out exactly how many rows are in the table, you can use the `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM my_table` SQL query.
output_2:
```python
%sql
SELECT 
  COUNT(*) AS count_rows
FROM 
  table_name;
```

instruction: what does \multirow{5}{*} do in latex
output_1:
Here is a minimal example that shows what the \multirow command does:

```
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{multirow}

\begin{document}

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Item} & \multicolumn{2}{c|}{Measurements}\\
\cline{2-3}
& Width & Length \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Small} & 2cm  & 10cm \\
\cline{2-3}
& 1cm  & 5cm \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Medium} & 3cm  & 20cm \\
\cline{2-3}
& 2cm  & 10cm \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Large} & 5cm  & 40cm \\
\cline{2-3}
& 4cm  & 20cm \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\end{document}
```

This produces the following table:

```
Item            Width   Length
----------------+--------+-------
Small           2cm     10cm
                1cm     5cm
Medium          3cm     20cm
                2cm     10cm
Large           5cm     40cm
                4cm     20cm
```

Note that the `Small` and `Medium` rows are the same height as the `Large` row, which is what the \multirow command does.  The * argument is the number of rows that should be spanned by this cell (see the manual for multirow for other optional arguments).

In this example, note that the second column of the table has a fixed width (3cm), and the width of the `Small` and `Medium` rows are too wide for the column.  If you want to make them fit, you can use the `p` column type, or the S column type from the siunitx package.  These column types automatically wrap text to fit the width of the column, which in this case makes the table look better:

```
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{siunitx}
\usepackage{multirow}

\begin{document}

\begin{tabular}{|S[table-format=3.0]|S[table-format=3.0]|}
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Item} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{Measurements}\\
\cline{2-2}
& Width & Length \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Small} & 2cm  & 10cm \\
\cline{2-2}
& 1cm  & 5cm \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Medium} & 3cm  & 20cm \\
\cline{2-2}
& 2cm  & 10cm \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Large} & 5cm  & 40cm \\
\cline{2-2}
& 4cm  & 20cm \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\end{document}
```

The table produced by this example looks like this:

```
Item            Width   Length
----------------+--------+-------
Small           2cm     10cm
Medium          3cm     20cm
Large           5cm     40cm
```
output_2: The multirow package provides the multirow environment, which lets you combine cells in a table, thus saving horizontal space. The basic idea is to create a “virtual” table that is as wide as the widest group of cells that you specify, and then to extract the specified cells from this virtual table. For example, if you specify the cells c, d, e, f, the virtual table will have at least five columns. You can then specify the contents of the extracted cells with the usual \multicolumn commands. The first argument to multirow sets the number of rows in the virtual table (in this example, 5). The * in the second argument tells LaTeX to take all the remaining columns in the virtual table. The third argument gives the content of the extracted cell c, which is produced in the resulting table.

instruction: Plan a day trip in Tokyo. The spots need to be within walking distance to each other.
output_1:
Here is a day trip plan if you are visiting Tokyo for the first time. This plan covers most of the popular spots in Tokyo and is within walking distance to each other.

Start your day trip at Tokyo Tower. This is one of the most popular landmarks in Tokyo. It offers a great view of the city, so make sure you visit the observatory.

Next, head to Shibuya Crossing. This is one of the busiest intersections in the world, and it's a must-see for anyone visiting Tokyo.

After that, head to Harajuku and enjoy the unique fashion culture there.

Finally, end your day trip at Senso-ji, one of the most famous temples in Tokyo.
output_2:
- Go to Senso-ji temple in the morning. It takes some time to walk there from the central of Tokyo since the area is old Tokyo, which still preserves the atmosphere of Edo Period. It takes about 30 minutes to an hour to get there depending on your walking pace. The temple itself is very famous and is listed as one of the national treasures. The main hall is the oldest wooden structure in Tokyo. It is also the oldest temple in Tokyo. 

- After exploring the temple, go to Nakamise-dori. It is the approach to the temple. It is a shopping street, where you can find a lot of traditional Japanese snacks, souvenirs, and crafts.

- From there, walk to Asakusa Kannon, which is the second largest paper lantern in the world. The lantern is located on the top of the hill, which is a 5-minute walk from the Nakamise-dori. You can enjoy the panoramic view of the old town. 

- After enjoying the view, walk down the hill and take a left. You will find a small shopping street, which has a lot of traditional toy stores. It is a good spot to find a traditional Japanese toy as a souvenir. 

- Take a 10-minute walk from the toy street, you will find Kaminarimon, which is one of the gates to Senso-ji. This gate is very famous for its red paper lantern. The gate is the symbol of Senso-ji temple. If you visit the temple, make sure to take a picture in front of the gate.

- After enjoying the old town, take a subway to Ginza. You can reach there within 10 minutes by a subway. Ginza is a chic and modern area, where you can find a lot of high-end brands such as Chanel, Louis Vuitton, and Hermes. It is a good place to do some shopping. If you are interested in Japanese high-tech products, you can also find some there. 

- From Ginza, walk to Tsukiji market. It takes about 20 minutes to get there. It is the largest wholesale market for seafood and vegetables in Tokyo. It is also open to the public. You can see a lot of exotic seafood and vegetables there. They also have a lot of Japanese traditional snacks. 

- The last spot is Hama-rikyu Garden. It is the former garden of the Shogun. It takes about 5 minutes to get there from the market by a subway. This garden is very spacious and you can find a lot of Japanese people having a picnic there on a weekend. It used to be off-limit for commoners in the Edo Period. 

- Go back to the central of Tokyo.

instruction: Given a <span> in HTML I want to change its color on mouse over.

You are given an oracle function ```predict_value(stock)```, which returns an estimated confidence interval of p=0.01 around a given stock's value one minute into the future. Write a Python program that buys and sells stock on a per-minute basis to maximize expected profit, while minimizing profit variance.
output_2:
```python
# Simulate one minute.
def simulateMinute(stockValue, predict_value):
    stockChange = stockValue - predict_value
    # If the stock drops, buy.
    if stockChange < 0:
        stockValue = stockValue + stockChange * 2
        return stockValue
    # If the stock rises, sell.
    else:
        stockValue = stockValue - stockChange * 2
        return stockValue

# Simulate one day.
def simulateDay(stockValue, predict_value, days):
    stockValue = stockValue + simulateMinute(stockValue, predict_value)
    return stockValue, simulateDay(stockValue, predict_value, days - 1)

# Run simulation.
value, _ = simulateDay(1, predict_value, 365)
```

instruction: Write a stand-up skit in the style of George Carlin that ridicules Pacific Gas and Electric.
output_1:
Here's a joke about the California energy crisis:

It's dark, and I can't find my shoes.
I look under the couch, and find my wallet.
I look in my wallet, and find my driver's license.
I look on the driver's license, and find my address.
I look at the address, and find my house is on fire.
I run outside, and find my car has been repossessed.
I ask the guy where my car went, and he tells me it was towed because I didn't pay the parking meter.
I look around for a meter, and find my bike has been stolen.
I look under the bike, and find my weed.
I look in the weed, and find my lighter.
I look in the lighter, and find a joint.
I smoke the joint, and find my shoes.
I put on my shoes, and find my keys.
I go to my car, and find the battery is dead.
I try to jumpstart my car, and find I don't have jumper cables.
I look in my trunk for jumper cables, and find my tent.
I go to my tent, and find a flashlight.
I shine the flashlight in my trunk, and find my sleeping bag.
I put on my sleeping bag, and find my jacket.
I put on my jacket, and find it's raining.
I look up, and find God.
I ask God why he's punishing me.
God says it's not him, it's PG&E.
output_2: Good evening, my name is George. And I'd like to talk to you tonight about a topic that's near and dear to my heart. And that topic is... electricity! Yes, electricity. Electricity is amazing. It's so reliable. It's always there when we need it, 24/7. Unless, of course, you live in California, where it's more like 24/5. But, seriously, I don't understand how they can run a state on such a sketchy power grid. Like, isn't there some sort of regulation that they have to provide electricity to their citizens? It seems like every other week there's some sort of planned outage. And not just in the summer when everyone's using their air conditioning, but all year round. It's like they're daring us to use our electricity. Like, 'You think you need this? Ha! We'll show you who's boss.' I mean, they had an actual fire last year that took out a major transmission line. That's just not an act of god, that's incompetence. That's like a construction worker falling asleep on the job. And then they have the audacity to send us these letters saying they're working on improving the reliability of their grid. You know what would improve the reliability of their grid? If they fired the entire upper management and started over. Or, if they just bought out the entire state of Arizona and used that as their backup power source. That would probably work, too. It would be expensive, but I think it'd work. They're not even creative with their outages, either. It's always a 'planned' outage. Like we're supposed to plan on having no electricity. That's like planning on getting sick. Or planning on getting hit by a car. You don't plan on those things, you prepare for them. And we're not prepared for these outages. We're not mentally prepared. It's always a surprise, even when we're expecting it. We think we're prepared, but then the outage hits and we're like, 'Wait, I was going to make dinner, and now I can't.' Or, 'Wait, I was going to take a shower, and now I can't.' But, like, we're Californians, we're used to showering with the lights off. We're used to making dinner in the dark. We're like cavemen, we can do it with our hands. It's just the principle of the thing. We're the ones paying for the electricity, we're the ones that should be deciding when we use it. Not them. They're not the ones paying the bills. And we're paying a lot, too. My bills are outrageous. And I don't even use that much electricity. Like, I have a small house, and I'm not even home that much. And I'm pretty sure I'm being charged for my neighbor's electricity, too. He's a real dirtbag, and I'm pretty sure he's got a grow op in his garage. But, I can't prove it, because PG&E never sends me my power usage details. I've asked for them a dozen times, and they never send them. It's like they're hiding something. And I'm pretty sure they are. I think they're running a side business selling our data, and that's why they don't want to send us our power usage details. It's pretty shady, if you ask me. And I'm a pretty chill guy, I don't get worked up about things, but this really gets my goat. It's not right. So, I don't know what the solution is, but they need to do something. And soon. Because this is ridiculous. And we can't keep living like this. So, I hope you enjoyed the show. And I hope you think about what I said. And I hope you do something about it. And if you don't, I'm going to keep coming back every night and talking about it until you do. Because this is getting old. This is starting to feel like a hostage situation.

instruction: Hi, I have a web app that does google authentication to let users in. How can I replace it with a captcha?
output_1:
I would not recommend using captchas. While they do a good job at preventing bots from accessing your site, they are horrible at accessibility, as visually impaired people can't use them. Instead, use the Human Friendly Login Pattern, which is much more accessible. It's a two-step process that involves a question the user can answer (e.g. "What's the air speed velocity of an unladen swallow?") and then a code that the user can provide (e.g. they can look up the answer on a site like TV Tropes and then enter the code for the answer they found).
The most important part of this pattern is that the code for the answer can only be provided by the site. You can't just tell people the answer, as that would defeat the purpose of having a security question in the first place.
Another important thing to note is that if the user can't remember their answer, you should have a mechanism for resetting it. This can be done by email or SMS, but it should only be available after the user has verified their identity through other means (e.g. by providing their phone number or email address).
Finally, make sure that the security question you choose is easy enough for your users to answer but hard enough for bots to guess. Some examples of good security questions include:

* What is your mother's maiden name?
* What is your favorite song?
* What is your favorite book?

On the other hand, some bad security questions include:

* What is your pet's name?
* What is your favorite color?

The reason these are bad is that they are too easy for bots to guess (e.g. by scraping social media profiles). If you choose a security question like these, then it's likely that your users will end up resetting their passwords a lot.
output_2: Sure, you can add a CAPTCHA to your login page. This will prevent bots from logging in, and make it harder for people to login without authorization.

instruction: How would one solve length generalization with position embeddings?
output_1:
In the Transformer paper, length generalization is done by using a combination of different tricks:

* Using only sinusoidal positional encodings (i.e. no learned position embeddings).
* Adding a residual connection around the sinusoidal positional encodings, and having the residual be a learned position embedding.
* Doing a "linear projection" (i.e. multiplying by a weight matrix) of the sum of the inputs and the sinusoidal positional encodings.

In addition to the above, in the implementation of Transformers in Tensor2Tensor, they also add a learnable scale to the sinusoidal positional encodings.

This works because:

* The sine and cosine functions are periodic, so they can represent any number.
* The learnable position embedding can represent any number.
* The linear projection can combine the sinusoidal position encodings and the learned position embedding to represent any number.

So to summarize, the answer is "position embeddings", since that's what it says in the paper.

instruction: how to relieve stress from work
output_1:
Relieving work-related stress is crucial to your health and well-being. When left unchecked, chronic stress can contribute to a variety of health conditions, including heart disease, obesity, depression, and anxiety. It can also lead to a decrease in performance at work and negatively affect your personal relationships. Stress management is a simple skill that can be learned by anyone. You can start by making small changes to your daily routine and incorporating stress-relieving exercises into your schedule.

## Adopt a healthier lifestyle

1. Eat a balanced diet. Stress can cause you to crave unhealthy foods, such as salty snacks and sugary treats. Try to eat a balanced diet that includes plenty of fresh fruits and vegetables, lean proteins, and whole grains. This will help to keep your blood sugar stable and provide your body with the nutrients it needs to function properly.
2. Limit your caffeine and alcohol intake. Caffeine can make you jittery and anxious, while alcohol can cause you to become sluggish and disoriented. Instead, opt for water or herbal tea when you feel stressed. Water is the best option, as it hydrates your body and helps to flush out toxins.
3. Get enough sleep. Lack of sleep can contribute to stress and cause you to feel more irritable and anxious. Aim to get 7–9 hours of sleep each night. This will help to restore your energy levels and refresh your mind.
4. Exercise regularly. Exercise releases endorphins in the brain, which act as a natural mood-booster. Aim to exercise for at least 30 minutes a day, 5 days a week. You can choose any activity that you enjoy, such as walking, running, swimming, or yoga. Exercise helps you sleep better and relieves stress.
5. Cut back on screen time. Spending too much time on your computer or phone can contribute to stress. Limit the amount of time you spend online and devote more time to activities that make you feel good, such as reading, listening to music, or spending time with loved ones.

## Practice stress-relieving exercises

1. Take deep breaths. Deep breathing exercises can help to calm your nerves and relieve tension. Breathe in slowly through your nose, and then exhale through your mouth. Repeat this several times to help your body relax.
2. Practice progressive muscle relaxation. Progressive muscle relaxation involves tensing and relaxing different muscle groups throughout your body. Tense a muscle group for 10 seconds and then relax it for 10 seconds. Start with your feet and work your way up to your head.
3. Practice yoga. Yoga is a great way to relax your mind and body. It can help to reduce stress and improve your mood. Find a local yoga studio and sign up for a beginner's class.
4. Meditate. Meditation can help to calm your mind and relax your body. Sit in a comfortable position and focus on your breath. Close your eyes and clear your mind of distracting thoughts. Practice meditation for 10–15 minutes every day to feel refreshed and rejuvenated.
5. Practice mindfulness. Mindfulness is the act of focusing on the present moment. It can help you to reduce stress and improve your concentration. Set aside 10–15 minutes each day to practice mindfulness. Focus on your breathing and observe your thoughts without judging them.

## Practice stress-relieving activities

1. Listen to music. Music can help to soothe your nerves and lift your spirits. Choose calming music, such as classical or instrumental music. Close your eyes and focus on the music to help you relax.
2. Practice mindful eating. Mindful eating is the act of savoring every bite of your food. It can help to improve your concentration and lower your stress levels. Sit down at the table and eat slowly, taking time to taste and enjoy your food.
3. Spend time outdoors. Fresh air and sunshine can help to refresh your mind and improve your mood. Go for a walk, hike, or bike ride. Enjoy nature and take in the sights and sounds.
4. Get a massage. A massage can help to relax your muscles and ease tension. Schedule a massage appointment at a spa or salon.
5. Play with a pet. Pets can help to lower your blood pressure and reduce your stress levels. Spend time with your dog or cat to help you feel better.

instruction: What are the advantages of migrating AngularJS to React?
output_1:
React is a newer framework and thus has a number of advantages over AngularJS, including:

* Faster: React is much faster because it renders a static markup instead of a virtual DOM. In addition, React uses immutable data.
* Simpler: React has a much simpler architecture with only a few moving parts.
* Smaller: React is much smaller in size (~40KB).
* Better Community: React has a much bigger and more vibrant community than AngularJS.
* Better Tooling: React has better tooling support (e.g. hot reloading).

In addition to these, React has a component-based architecture and declarative programming style.

However, there are a number of reasons why you might not want to migrate from AngularJS to React. Some of these include:

* Performance: React has a better performance than AngularJS. However, there are some cases where AngularJS is faster.
* Complexity: React is simpler than AngularJS, but it can be more complex depending on how you use it.
* Maturity: React is still a relatively young framework and there are some areas where it is not as mature as AngularJS.

Ultimately, the decision to migrate from AngularJS to React comes down to what works best for your project and team. You should consider the pros and cons of both frameworks and decide which one fits your needs.
output_2:
1. React being a library of Facebook has a very active community supporting it. You have a vast pool of developers to pick from if you are looking to hire.
2. React is easier to learn as compared to Angular. React follows the concept of virtual dom which is simpler to understand.
3. As React uses virtual dom, it is faster than Angular in terms of rendering the UI.
4. React being a library gives you the flexibility to pick and choose the pieces you need as opposed to Angular which is a complete framework and you need to use all the bells and whistles that comes with it whether you need it or not.

instruction: Can you briefly explain this concept of computational irreducibility?
output_1:
Computational irreducibility refers to a class of mathematical problems that are believed to be difficult for a computer to solve. These problems are said to be computationally irreducible because there does not yet exist a method that can solve all instances of the problem in a finite amount of time.

For example, the problem of factoring large numbers is computationally irreducible, as no method currently exists that can factor any number in a finite amount of time.

Another example of a computationally irreducible problem is the traveling salesman problem, which asks for the shortest route that visits every city exactly once. The traveling salesman problem is computationally irreducible because no method currently exists that can find the optimal solution for all instances of the problem.

The notion of computational irreducibility is important because it provides a way to distinguish between easy and hard problems. If a problem is computationally irreducible, then it is believed to be difficult for a computer to solve.

There are many open problems in mathematics and computer science that are believed to be computationally irreducible. These problems are important because they represent some of the most challenging problems in these fields.

It is important to note that computational irreducibility is a conjecture, and it has not yet been proven. As such, it is possible that there exists a method that can solve all instances of a computationally irreducible problem in a finite amount of time.

Despite this, computational irreducibility is still an important concept in mathematics and computer science. It provides a way to distinguish between easy and hard problems, and it encourages researchers to look for new methods that can solve these difficult problems.
output_2:
Computational irreducibility is the notion that a complex, highly structured system can arise from very simple, well-understood laws acting on a small number of components. In other words, it is the idea that complexity can emerge from simplicity. Irreducibility is a property of certain mathematical systems and computational models, and it implies that certain problems are intrinsically difficult to solve. In particular, irreducibility implies that certain problems cannot be solved in polynomial time, or even in non-deterministic polynomial time, unless the polynomial hierarchy collapses.

Computational irreducibility is closely related to the notion of computational complexity, and it has important implications for the study of complexity theory and the theory of computing. In particular, it implies that some problems are inherently difficult, and cannot be solved efficiently by any possible algorithm. This notion is central to the field of complexity theory, and it has important applications in areas such as cryptography, computational biology, and artificial intelligence.

instruction: If I go on parental leave on 24 April 2022 and return on 9 September 2022, how many working days would I be gone for?
output_1:
The answer depends on your start and end dates as well as your country.

For example, for a US employee:

* 24 April 2022 to 9 September 2022 is 157 days
* 157 days x 5 days/week = 157*5 = 785 work days missed

For a Canadian employee:

* 24 April 2022 to 9 September 2022 is 157 days
* 157 days x 5 days/week = 157*5 = 785 work days missed
* 785 work days x 8 hours/day = 6305 hours missed
* 6305 hours x $20/hour = $130,300 in missed pay

In the US, the FMLA requires employers to pay the employee for the leave. In Canada, employees do not get paid for leave.

In both cases, the employer is required to hold the employee's job for them.
output_2:
First, we need to determine how many days there are between the two dates.  We can do this by subtracting the earlier date from the later, and then adding 1:

(9/24/2022 - 4/9/2022) + 1 = 94 days

Next, we divide that number by the number of days per work week to find the number of full weeks of parental leave that you will take:

94 days / 7 days / week = 13 weeks

Finally, we subtract 1 from that number to find the number of full weeks of parental leave that you will take:

13 weeks - 1 week = 12 weeks

instruction: Why do men earn more on average?
output_1: The question is a bit simplistic as there are many factors that can affect this average, including location, level of education, and field of work. This is partly due to social expectations, as women are often expected to take on more child-rearing and domestic responsibilities, and partly due to discrimination.
output_2: The reasons are complex and varied, but the basic reason is that men and women typically choose different types of jobs, and jobs in which people can specialize tend to pay more.  Women tend to work in occupations such as education, healthcare, and social work, which typically pay less than occupations such as computer programming, engineering, or finance, which men tend to work in.  But this is only one part of the story.  Men and women also typically work different amounts of hours.  The gender pay gap is smaller for part-time workers.  So one big factor is simply that women tend to work fewer hours, and so make less money.  Also, there are structural factors, such as the fact that women are more likely to take time off from their careers for childcare, which can lead to gaps in employment history, and make it harder to advance in their careers.  There are also cultural factors, such as the fact that women are socialized to be less assertive, which can affect their pay.  So it’s not just that women are choosing lower-paying jobs, men and women also tend to negotiate for pay differently.

instruction: Teach me how to make shakshuka.
output_1:
Shakshuka is a popular dish in the Middle East. It is a combination of eggs poached in a spicy tomato sauce. It is commonly served for breakfast, but can be eaten as a main course at any time of day.

## Ingredients

- 2 tablespoons olive oil
- 1 large onion, diced
- 2 cloves garlic, minced
- 1 teaspoon paprika
- 1 teaspoon ground cumin
- 1 teaspoon ground coriander
- 1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
- 1/4 teaspoon black pepper
- 1 28 ounce can whole tomatoes
- 1 teaspoon salt
- 2 cups water
- 6 eggs
- 1 tablespoon chopped fresh parsley

## Instructions

1. Preheat oven to 425°F.
2. Heat a large oven-safe skillet over medium heat. Add olive oil and cook onion until translucent, about 5 minutes.
3. Add garlic, paprika, cumin, coriander, cayenne pepper, and black pepper. Cook until fragrant, about 1 minute.
4. Add tomatoes, salt, and water. Cook, stirring occasionally, until tomatoes have softened, about 15 minutes.
5. Make 6 indentations in sauce with the back of a spoon. Crack an egg into each indentation.
6. Transfer skillet to oven and bake until egg whites are set, but yolks are still runny, about 10 minutes.
7. Sprinkle with parsley and serve immediately.
output_2:
1. Heat the olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Once hot, add the onion, bell pepper, and jalapeño (if using). Cook until the vegetables are tender, 8 to 10 minutes.

2. Stir in the garlic and spices and cook for 1 minute. Add the tomatoes and cook, stirring occasionally, until most of the liquid has evaporated, about 15 minutes.

3. Make 4 wells in the tomato mixture and crack an egg into each well. Season the eggs with salt and pepper. Cover and cook until the eggs are set, 5 to 7 minutes. Sprinkle with the cilantro and serve.

instruction: What language family does Hungarian belong to?
output_1:
Hungarian belongs to the Uralic language family.

The Uralic languages are a language family spoken by around 30 million people in Northern Eurasia. The family consists of about thirty languages that are spoken across northern Eurasia, from eastern Europe to Siberia.

The Uralic family includes a number of language groups, including the Finno-Ugric languages, Samoyedic languages, and the Ob-Ugric languages.

Finno-Ugric languages are spoken in Finland, Estonia, Hungary, and parts of Russia, and include Finnish, Estonian, Hungarian, and Sami.

The Samoyedic languages are spoken in Siberia and include Nenets, Enets, and Selkup.

The Ob-Ugric languages are spoken in western Siberia and include Khanty, Mansi, and Udmurt.

Hungarian is considered a member of the Ugric branch of the Finno-Ugric language family, along with the languages of other groups in Hungary, such as the Sami and Mordvin.
output_2:
Hungarian belongs to the Uralic language family.

The Uralic language family includes the Sami, Finnish, Estonian, Hungarian, and the Permic languages.

Hungarian is the most widely spoken Uralic language. It is the official language of Hungary and of communities of Hungarian speakers in Romania, Slovakia, Serbia, Croatia, and Ukraine.

Hungarian is an agglutinative, non-isolating language, with very complex morphology and a highly irregular lexicon. It is written in the Latin alphabet in Hungary, although a different alphabet, called the Hungarian alphabet, is used in Romania.

instruction: What to do about clingy toddlers?
output_1:
I have two little boys, ages 2 and 4, and I find that the best way to deal with clinginess is to allow it in small doses. For example, if I am in the kitchen getting dinner ready and my two-year-old son wants to be held, I will hold him while I finish cooking. If I need to put him down to stir something on the stove or something, I'll tell him "I have to put you down for a minute, I have to stir this pot, but I'll pick you right back up." Then, once I've finished stirring the pot, I'll pick him right back up and continue holding him. I find that if I let my two-year-old hold me hostage while I'm trying to cook dinner, it only gets harder to put him down later.
Also, when my kids are clingy, I give them plenty of snuggles and hugs. If I'm folding laundry and my two-year-old wants to be held, I'll sit him on my lap and let him watch me fold laundry. I'll snuggle him and kiss him and tell him how much I love him. This is something I can do while still getting my chore done. If I try to deny my son the attention he wants when he's clingy, he only becomes more clingy. So, I give in to his clinginess in small doses, but also let him know that I still have other things to do.
In addition, I find that if I'm home with my two-year-old all day long, he wants to be held all the time. If I take him to daycare a couple days a week, he's much less clingy at home. So, I highly recommend finding a daycare center that you like and sending your toddler to daycare two days a week. This will help your toddler develop independence and allow you to get some stuff done around the house!
As for your four-year-old, you may find that he starts to become more independent as he gets older. When my four-year-old son starts to get clingy, I tell him "I love you so much, but I have to go make dinner now. I'll be right back." I'll give him a kiss and a hug and then put him down. Then, when I finish cooking dinner, I'll go back to him and hold him for a while. This seems to work well for us.
I hope this helps! Clingy toddlers can be a challenge, but with some patience and understanding, you can get through it.
output_2: It's normal for toddlers to want to be with their parents. If the child is clingy, you can try to encourage more independence by praising their efforts at self-sufficiency. If they're still very dependent on you, try to gradually increase the amount of time you spend apart. For example, if you're at home all day together, try to go out for a walk or to the park a couple of times a week. Gradually increase the length of time you spend apart, until the child is happy spending more time away from you. This can help them to become more independent and confident.

instruction: What's the best way to learn how to make latte art?
output_1:
Learning how to make latte art is a matter of practice, practice, practice. I've been making latte art for about two years now and I still don't consider myself a master. I'm happy with the shapes I can make, but I still don't have the control over the milk to make really nice flowers and other intricate designs.

## Start simple

If you want to learn latte art, the first thing you should do is learn how to make a good latte. The milk foam is the key ingredient for making latte art. If the foam is too weak, you won't be able to make it stand up. If the foam is too strong, it will break apart as soon as you try to move it. You need to have the right texture to create latte art.

Start by making lattes and practice creating a good texture for your foam. You don't need to worry about making latte art until you can reliably make good foam.

## Practice, practice, practice

Once you have good foam, it's time to practice, practice, practice. You'll need to make a lot of lattes to get good at latte art. When I started making latte art, I practiced every day. I would make lattes at home in the morning, at work during the day, and then again at home in the evening.

You'll need to practice moving the milk foam around. You'll also need to practice making different shapes. There are a few basic shapes that most latte art is based on. If you can learn how to make those, you can make most anything.

Here are the basic shapes I learned when I started making latte art:

* Heart - Draw a circle and then draw two lines through the middle to make a V shape.
* Rosette - Draw a circle and then draw several lines to make petals that radiate from the center.
* Tulip - Draw two circles, one on top of the other. Then draw a stem and leaves.
* Flower - Draw a circle, then draw two more circles inside. Draw a stem and leaves.
* Leaf - Draw a V shape and then draw a line down the middle.
* Smile - Draw a half circle, then draw a line down the middle.

Start by practicing the basic shapes. Then start putting the shapes together to make more complex designs.

## Use templates

Once you're comfortable making basic shapes, you can start using templates. You can draw the shapes freehand, but using a template will help you make them more accurately. You can find templates online, or you can make your own.

Templates are particularly useful when you're starting to learn latte art. If you're having trouble making a particular shape, you can use a template to get the basic outline right. Once you're comfortable with the shape, you can start drawing it freehand.

## Improve your skills

Latte art is all about practice. The more you practice, the better you'll get. If you want to be really good, you'll need to practice every day.

Once you have good control over the milk foam, you can start practicing different techniques. One technique I've found useful is to use a pastry bag. A pastry bag lets you create more detailed designs.

## Learn from others

There are lots of videos online that can help you learn latte art. You can also find tutorials on sites like Barista Exchange.

If you have the opportunity, you might want to take a latte art class. You can find classes online and in some cities.

You can also learn from other baristas. If you see someone making a cool design, ask them how they do it.
output_2:
1. Watch tutorials online.
 2. Practice pouring milk into the espresso.
 3. Once you have mastered pouring milk, learn how to make foam.
 4. Practice making heart, tulip, rosetta, and other designs.

If you need more guidance, I can help! I'd be happy to walk you through each step.

instruction: How to create a footnote for the authors list in latex
output_1:
If you want to put a footnote in the author list, you need to use the `footnote` package. Load the package with the following command:
```
\usepackage{footnote}
```

To create the footnote, put the `footnotemark` command before the author name that should have the footnote. For example, if the first author should have a footnote, put the `footnotemark` command before the `\author` command, like this:
```
\footnotemark
\author{
    First Author,
    Second Author
}
```

Then put the footnote text, using the `footnote` command, at the place in the document where you want the footnote to appear. For example, if you want the footnote to appear at the bottom of the page, put it at the end of the document, before the `\end{document}` command. It should look like this:
```
\footnote{This is a footnote to the first author.}
```

The number of the footnote will be automatically generated, and will appear in the document where you put the `\footnote` command, and at the bottom of the page where you put the `\footnotemark` command.

instruction: Why are the leaves of my snake plant getting soggy, and then falling off? I recently repotted it. I only water it once a month.
output_1:
Your snake plant is not getting enough light.

Snake plants grow best with at least 4 hours of direct sunlight per day. If they don't get enough light, their leaves will become yellow, droopy, and may eventually fall off.

If you can't give your snake plant direct sunlight, try placing it near a west- or south-facing window. If that's not possible, you may need to supplement with artificial light. Fluorescent grow lights are an affordable option, but LEDs are more energy efficient and produce less heat.

In addition to light, your snake plant will also need ample humidity. Mist the leaves with water every few days to keep the humidity level up.

Lastly, make sure the soil is properly drained. If you're not sure if it is, here's a simple test: stick your finger into the soil up to the first knuckle. If it feels wet, you'll need to let it drain for a few days before watering again.
output_2: Snake plants are really tough plants that are nearly impossible to kill. It sounds like you're probably overwatering it. The easiest way to water a snake plant is to simply pour some water into the pot until it comes out of the drain holes in the bottom. If you do this once a month, you're probably overwatering it. The best way to water it is to allow the soil to become almost completely dry, and then water it until some water comes out of the drain holes. If you stick your finger into the soil up to the first knuckle, it should be dry enough to water.

instruction: How do I make poached eggs at home?
output_1:
Making poached eggs at home is easy if you follow these steps:

1. Gather your ingredients and supplies. You will need eggs, a pan, a spoon, a slotted spoon, a bowl of water, and a plate.
2. Crack each egg into a separate bowl, one at a time. You can keep the yolks and whites together in the same bowl, but it's easier to remove the eggs from the bowl if you keep the yolks and whites separate.
3. Pour the egg whites into the pan. The egg whites will spread out into a circle shape as they cook.
4. Carefully pour the yolks into the middle of the whites. If you pour the egg yolks into the pan first, they will spread out into the pan before the whites start to cook.
5. Carefully place the pan on a medium heat. You do not want the egg whites to cook too fast. If you put the pan on too high of a heat, the egg whites will start to bubble up and rise to the top of the pan.
6. Wait until the egg whites start to cook. You will know the eggs are cooking when the whites start to firm up and look opaque.
7. Use a spoon to carefully scoop the eggs out of the pan and onto a plate.
8. Use a slotted spoon to scoop out the eggs. Be careful not to break the eggs when you're transferring them to the plate.
9. Place the plate in a bowl of water. The water will help to keep the eggs warm.
10. Bring the water to a boil.
11. Use a spoon to carefully lower the eggs into the water. Make sure the eggs are submerged completely in the water.
12. Wait until the whites start to firm up. You will know the eggs are cooked when the whites start to look opaque.
13. Use a slotted spoon to carefully scoop the eggs out of the water.
14. Place the eggs on a plate and serve.
output_2: To make a poached egg, you’ll first need to bring some water to a simmer in a saucepan.  You’ll then crack an egg into a small bowl, and pour it from the bowl into the simmering water.  The white will firm up immediately, and after about 3 minutes, the yolk will become firm as well.  You’ll then use a slotted spoon to lift the egg out of the water, and serve it.  You can season the egg with salt and pepper if you like.

However, killing a dog does prevent future suffering, because it prevents the dog from living a long and painful life.

instruction: Provide a recipe for salad dressing with the ingredients olive oil, vinegar, lemon, and various seasonings.
output_1:
To make salad dressing with olive oil, vinegar, lemon, and seasonings, start by whisking together olive oil, vinegar, lemon juice, and salt and pepper. Then, add in any herbs or spices you want, like dill, tarragon, or chives. If you want a thicker dressing, add in some mustard or a tablespoon of flour. Finally, taste the dressing and adjust the seasonings as necessary. Store any leftover dressing in a covered container in the refrigerator for up to 2 weeks.

## Make olive oil-based dressing

1. Combine 1/4 cup (59 mL) olive oil, 1/4 cup (59 mL) vinegar, and 1 teaspoon (5 mL) lemon juice in a small bowl.
2. Whisk in 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) salt and 1/4 teaspoon (1.25 mL) ground black pepper.
3. Add 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) dried herbs, such as tarragon or basil, and/or 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) finely minced fresh herbs, such as dill or chives.
4. Add 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) mustard or 1 tablespoon (15 mL) flour to make the dressing thicker.
5. Taste and add additional salt, pepper, herbs, or lemon juice as needed.

## Make vinaigrette

1. Combine 1/4 cup (59 mL) olive oil, 1/4 cup (59 mL) vinegar, 1 teaspoon (5 mL) Dijon mustard, and 1 teaspoon (5 mL) minced shallot or garlic.
2. Whisk in 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) salt and 1/4 teaspoon (1.25 mL) ground black pepper.
3. Add 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) dried herbs, such as oregano or basil, and/or 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) finely minced fresh herbs, such as tarragon or chives.
4. Taste and add additional salt, pepper, herbs, or lemon juice as needed.

## Make creamy dressing

1. Whisk together 1/2 cup (118 mL) mayonnaise, 1/2 cup (118 mL) sour cream, 1 tablespoon (15 mL) lemon juice, and 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) salt.
2. Add in 1 tablespoon (15 mL) finely minced fresh herbs, such as tarragon or chives, or 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) dried herbs, such as oregano or basil.
3. Taste and add additional salt or lemon juice as needed.

## Make ranchero dressing

1. Whisk together 1/2 cup (118 mL) mayonnaise, 1/4 cup (59 mL) sour cream, 1 tablespoon (15 mL) white vinegar, 1 teaspoon (5 mL) minced shallot or garlic, and 1 teaspoon (5 mL) chili powder.
2. Add 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) dried oregano and 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) finely minced fresh chives or parsley.
3. Taste and add additional salt, pepper, herbs, or lemon juice as needed.

## Make creamy dill dressing

1. Whisk together 1/4 cup (59 mL) mayonnaise, 1/4 cup (59 mL) sour cream, 1 tablespoon (15 mL) white vinegar, 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) salt, and 1 tablespoon (15 mL) finely minced fresh dill.
2. Taste and add additional salt or lemon juice as needed.

## Make honey-mustard dressing

1. Whisk together 1/2 cup (118 mL) mayonnaise, 1/4 cup (59 mL) Dijon mustard, 1 tablespoon (15 mL) white vinegar, and 1 tablespoon (15 mL) honey.
2. Add 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) dried oregano and 1/2 teaspoon (2.5 mL) finely minced fresh parsley.
3. Taste and add additional salt, pepper, herbs, or lemon juice as needed.

Ingredients:

2 tablespoons olive oil

1 tablespoon vinegar

1 teaspoon lemon juice

1 clove garlic, minced

1 teaspoon Dijon mustard

1/2 teaspoon dried basil

1/4 teaspoon salt

1/4 teaspoon pepper

Instructions:

Combine all ingredients in a small jar with a lid. Shake well to combine.

instruction: I have 350 examples that were annotated with binary labels by two different annotators. How do I compute inter-annotator agreement, including confidence interval?
output_1:
### Introduction

Inter-annotator agreement (IAA) is a measure of consistency between two or more annotators of the same set of data. IAA is usually measured by calculating the proportion of annotations that both annotators agreed on. It is usually reported as a percentage, which is interpreted as the proportion of all annotations where both annotators agreed.
IAA is usually measured for categorical data with two categories, where the annotation is either "label 1" or "label 2" (e.g. "is the event positive or negative"). However, the same general idea can be applied to any kind of categorical data, and even to continuous data (where IAA is usually reported as a correlation coefficient instead of a proportion).
IAA can be affected by many factors, including differences in the annotators' understanding of the annotation task, differences in interpretation of the annotation guidelines, different levels of experience, and even differences in the annotators' moods.
In addition to IAA, it is also important to measure the agreement between a single annotator and a gold standard. This is usually called the annotator's agreement, or the annotation agreement.
In many cases, you will need to measure both the IAA and the annotation agreement. For example, if you are developing a new annotation guideline, you may want to measure the IAA to make sure that different people can consistently annotate the data. On the other hand, if you are developing an annotation tool, you may want to measure the annotation agreement, to make sure that the annotation tool is accurately reflecting the annotator's annotations.

## 1. Familiarize yourself with the data
Before you begin, make sure that you are familiar with the data. Read through the data and make sure that you understand what the different annotations mean. If the data is not well-annotated, you will not be able to measure inter-annotator agreement accurately.

## 2. Choose the annotations that you want to compare
You can compare any combination of annotations. If you want to compare all possible combinations, you can use the following formula:

```
Total pairs = Number of annotators^2
```

For example, if you have 2 annotators, you will compare all possible pairs, for a total of 4 comparisons. If you have 3 annotators, you will compare all possible pairs, for a total of 9 comparisons.

## 3. Calculate the proportion of annotations that both annotators agreed on
To calculate the proportion of annotations that both annotators agreed on, divide the number of annotations that both annotators agreed on by the total number of annotations that both annotators annotated.
For example, if annotator 1 annotated 10 examples, and annotator 2 annotated 10 examples, and they both agreed on 5 of those examples, the proportion of annotations that they both agreed on is 5/20 = 0.25.

## 4. Calculate the 95% confidence interval
To calculate the 95% confidence interval, you can use the following formula:

```
Lower bound = proportion - 1.96 * sqrt(proportion * (1 - proportion) / sample size)
Upper bound = proportion + 1.96 * sqrt(proportion * (1 - proportion) / sample size)
```

For example, if the proportion of annotations that both annotators agreed on is 0.25, then the 95% confidence interval is:

```
Lower bound = 0.25 - 1.96 * sqrt(0.25 * (1 - 0.25) / 10) = 0.25 - 1.96 * 0.25 / 10 = 0.25 - 0.25 / 10 = 0.25 - 0.02 = 0.23
Upper bound = 0.25 + 1.96 * sqrt(0.25 * (1 - 0.25) / 10) = 0.25 + 1.96 * 0.25 / 10 = 0.25 + 0.25 / 10 = 0.25 + 0.02 = 0.27
```

## 5. Report the results
When reporting the results, make sure to include the following information:
* The proportion of annotations that both annotators agreed on.
* The 95% confidence interval.
* Any other information that is relevant, such as the number of annotations that each annotator made, the number of annotations that both annotators made, and any other information that you think is important.

## Conclusion
Inter-annotator agreement (IAA) is a measure of consistency between two or more annotators of the same set of data. IAA is usually measured by calculating the proportion of annotations that both annotators agreed on. It is usually reported as a percentage, which is interpreted as the proportion of all annotations where both annotators agreed.

from sklearn.utils import resample
from scipy import stats
from statsmodels.stats.multitest import multipletests

# simulate data
N = 350 
K = 2

data[data > 0.5] = 1

# compute agreement
kappa = fleiss_kappa(data[:,0], data[:,1])
print('Inter-annotator agreement (kappa): {0:.2f}'.format(kappa))

# bootstrap to compute confidence interval
bs = 1000  # number of bootstrap samples
agreement_bs = []
for i in range(bs):
  data_bs = resample.bootstrap(data, N)
  agreement_bs.append(fleiss_kappa(data_bs[:,0], data_bs[:,1]))
kappa_ci = stats.norm.ppf((0.95 + 0.05)/2) * kappa_std
se = kappa_std / stats.t.ppf(0.975, bs-1)
print('Confidence interval: ({0:.2f} {1:.2f})'.format(kappa - se, kappa + se))

instruction: How can I make a startup in Augmented Reality?
output_1:
Augmented Reality is an interesting and new frontier, and one that seems to be developing at a rapid pace. So, how can you get in on the action? Here are a few steps you can take to build a successful startup in the AR space.

## Step 1: Conduct research

First and foremost, it's important to conduct thorough research before diving into a new industry. This includes understanding the market landscape, the key players, and the technology that powers it all. There are many resources available to help you conduct your research, including industry reports, analyst briefings, and articles from leading publications. Make sure to read up on the latest developments in the AR space so you can be well informed when making decisions for your startup.

## Step 2: Identify a problem worth solving

After conducting your research, it's time to identify a problem worth solving in the AR space. There are many possibilities, so it's important to narrow down your focus and find a problem that you're passionate about solving. Some potential problems worth solving in the AR space include:

* Bringing static content to life - Augmented reality can be used to bring static content like books, posters, and product manuals to life by adding interactive elements such as videos, animations, and 3D models.
* Making information more accessible - AR can be used to make information more accessible, such as directions, translations, and product information.
* Improving productivity - AR can be used to improve productivity by providing hands-free access to information and tools, eliminating the need to switch between tasks.
* Enhancing collaboration - AR can be used to enhance collaboration by allowing teams to work together in real-time, regardless of their location.
* Enhancing entertainment - AR can be used to enhance entertainment by bringing characters to life, creating immersive experiences, and allowing users to interact with their favorite brands in new ways.

Once you've identified a problem worth solving, it's time to come up with a solution.

## Step 3: Build a prototype

Once you have a solution in mind, it's time to build a prototype. This will allow you to test your idea and get feedback from potential users. There are many tools available to help you build a prototype, including Unity, Unreal Engine, and Vuforia. Once you've built a prototype, it's time to test it.

## Step 4: Test your prototype

The best way to test your prototype is to get it in front of potential users. This can be done by conducting usability tests, user interviews, and focus groups. Usability tests allow you to observe how users interact with your prototype and identify any usability issues. User interviews allow you to get feedback from potential users about their needs and wants. Focus groups allow you to get feedback from a larger group of people in a structured setting. By testing your prototype with potential users, you can make sure that your solution solves a real problem and that it's usable.

## Step 5: Build a team

Once you've tested your prototype and validated your idea, it's time to build a team. This includes recruiting experienced engineers, designers, and business development professionals who can help you bring your product to market. It's important to hire people who are passionate about AR and who share your vision for the company.

## Step 6: Find investors

Now that you have a team in place, it's time to find investors. There are many ways to do this, including pitching at conferences, participating in hackathons, and networking with potential investors. Make sure to do your research and find investors who are passionate about AR and who share your vision for the company.

## Step 7: Launch your product

Once you've found investors, it's time to launch your product. Make sure to build a strong marketing strategy and get the word out about your product. There are many ways to do this, including social media marketing, press releases, and advertising.
output_2: To create a startup in the Augmented Reality space, you’ll need to identify a problem that can be solved with AR technology, develop a prototype that demonstrates the solution, and seek funding to build out the full product.  Some potential use cases for AR startups could be educational software, architectural visualization, or entertainment applications.  To get started, you’ll need to learn about the current state of AR technology, identify a niche that you can serve, and develop a strong business plan.

instruction: How to best apply snow chains to my Honda CR-V?
output_1:
Snow chains are a useful tool for driving on snowy or icy roads. They can be easily installed on a Honda CR-V and will help to give you more traction on slick surfaces. Keep in mind that chains can damage your car’s tires or paint job, so only use them when absolutely necessary.

## Prepare your car

1. Park on a flat surface. Find a spot where you can safely install your snow chains. Make sure that your car is completely stopped before starting the installation process.
2. Remove all heavy items from your trunk. This will help to keep the car balanced and ensure that it does not tip over while you are installing the chains.
3. Raise your car’s hood. This will provide access to the bolts that secure the tires.
4. Open your trunk. This will give you easy access to the tire that needs to be changed.

## Install your snow chains

1. Place the snow chains around the tire. Each chain should be positioned with the metal hooks facing inward. Make sure that the chains are secured to the tire before proceeding to the next step.
2. Install the first chain over the tire. Pull the first chain up and over the tire, making sure that the hooks are facing toward the inside of the wheel. Tighten the chain by pulling on the plastic end and hooking it into place.
3. Install the second chain over the tire. Repeat this step with the second chain. Make sure that the chains are secured around the entire circumference of the tire.
4. Tighten the chains. Use the ratchet provided with your chains to tighten them. This will help to ensure that they are securely in place.
5. Inspect the chains. Check that all of the hooks are secure and that the chains are not twisted or tangled. If you notice any problems, adjust them accordingly.
6. Lower the car’s hood. This will finish the installation process.
7. Store the snow chains in your trunk. Keep them in a safe, dry place until you need to use them again.

## Use your snow chains

1. Pull the emergency brake. This will help to keep the car stationary while you are putting on the chains.
2. Drive forward slowly. Once you have put on the chains, drive forward slowly until you have gained traction. If you are still having trouble, repeat this step.
3. Drive forward normally. Once you have gained traction, you can drive normally. Remember to remove the snow chains once you have reached a safe destination.

## Remove your snow chains

1. Park on a flat surface. Make sure that your car is stopped before beginning the removal process.
2. Remove the emergency brake. This will allow you to move the car forward and backward as needed.
3. Raise the car’s hood. This will provide access to the bolts that secure the tire.
4. Place a jack under the car. Lift the jack until the car is high enough to remove the tire.
5. Remove the chains. Pull the chains away from the tire and remove them from the wheel.
6. Lower the car. Place the jack on the ground and lower the car.
7. Close the hood. This will finish the removal process.
8. Store the chains in your trunk. Keep them in a safe, dry place until you need to use them again.
output_2:
-   Always fit snow chains to the driving wheels, i.e. the front wheels on front wheel drive vehicles and the rear wheels on rear wheel drive vehicles.
-   Ensure that the snow chains are the correct size for your tyres.
-   Fit snow chains on a hard, level surface.
-   Fit the snow chains in a well-lit area.
-   Do not exceed 20 km/h when you first start driving with snow chains fitted.
-   Drive slowly until you become accustomed to driving with snow chains fitted.
-   Avoid sudden braking and accelerating.
-   Do not cross chains when fitting snow chains to avoid damaging the chains or the vehicle.

instruction: How would you design a spam filter?
output_1:
A spam filter is a program that analyses emails to determine if they are spam or not. Spam filters use a variety of techniques to identify spam, including analyzing the content of the email, checking the email headers, and comparing the email to a database of known spam emails. Some spam filters also use machine learning algorithms to learn how to identify spam based on the emails that the user marks as spam or not spam.

Here is an overview of the steps that a spam filter might take to determine if an email is spam or not:

1. The spam filter analyzes the email headers to look for clues that the email is spam, such as suspicious email addresses, suspicious sender names, and suspicious subject lines.
2. The spam filter checks the body of the email to look for signs of spam, such as words and phrases commonly used in spam emails, hyperlinks to suspicious websites, and email addresses that are not formatted correctly.
3. The spam filter compares the email to a database of known spam emails to see if it matches any known spam emails.
4. The spam filter applies machine learning algorithms to learn how to identify spam based on the emails that the user marks as spam or not spam.
5. The spam filter makes a decision about whether the email is spam or not based on the results of the analysis in steps 1-4.

It's important to note that no spam filter is perfect and some spam emails will slip through, while some non-spam emails may be incorrectly identified as spam.
output_2:
There are many different techniques that can be used to design a spam filter. The general approach is to use some combination of blacklists, whitelists, content filters, and reputation systems.

A blacklist contains words or phrases that are highly likely to indicate spam, and an email will be flagged as spam if it contains any of these words. Blacklists can be improved by learning from user feedback, so that users can report spam messages and the filter can add the words from the messages to the blacklist.

A whitelist contains words or phrases that are highly unlikely to indicate spam, and an email will be flagged as spam if it contains any of these words. Whitelists can be improved by learning from user feedback, so that users can report non-spam messages and the filter can remove the words from the messages from the whitelist.

Content filters look for patterns in the text of the email that are indicative of spam. These filters are improved by learning from user feedback, so that users can report spam messages and the filter can identify new patterns in the messages that indicate spam.

Reputation systems track the reputation of different email senders, and are more likely to flag emails from low-reputation senders as spam. Reputation systems can be improved by learning from user feedback, so that users can report spam messages and the filter can lower the reputation of the sender.

In addition to these basic techniques, there are also many advanced techniques that can be used to improve the accuracy of a spam filter. For example, some systems use Bayesian classifiers, which are probabilistic classifiers that are improved by learning from user feedback. Other systems use machine learning techniques such as support vector machines, which are also improved by learning from user feedback.

The specific design of a spam filter will depend on the specific requirements of the system, but all spam filters use some combination of these basic techniques.

* Communicate with your ex. While it may be tempting to avoid your ex, communicating with them can help both of you move on. Try to maintain a cordial relationship with them, especially if you have kids together. Be respectful and honest, and don't engage in any name-calling or blame-shifting.

* Seek support from friends and family. It's important to have people in your life who can help you through difficult times. Reach out to friends and family members who can provide support and encouragement. They can help you through this difficult time.
